1. Executive Summary

This paper addresses a simple democratic problem currently being buried under technical language: if advanced AI is so dangerous that ordinary citizens, researchers, small companies, hobbyists, accountants named Dave, and open-weight communities must be restricted from building or modifying it, then the same danger applies to Anthropic, OpenAI, and every other private frontier lab.

OpenAI describes itself as a structure in which a nonprofit foundation controls a public benefit corporation, OpenAI Group PBC. Anthropic describes itself as a Public Benefit Corporation whose purpose is the responsible development and maintenance of advanced AI for the long-term benefit of humanity. These are governance claims, not democratic mandates. Neither arrangement turns a private lab into a sovereign public authority. Neither makes Sam Altman or Dario Amodei elected guardians of permissible intelligence.  

Dario Amodei has argued that open source does not work the same way in AI, that open-weight systems are not the same as traditional open-source software, and that large models still require inference hosting. That distinction is real enough to discuss. The error begins when the distinction is smuggled into a hierarchy of legitimacy: closed corporate model good, public/open model suspicious.  

This paper therefore introduces the Coca-Cola Equivalence Test: if a private company is allowed to make and sell a powerful product because it has internal governance, lawyers, branding, safety committees, and an executive who speaks in paragraphs, then other private actors cannot automatically be treated as illegitimate merely because their method is more open. Coca-Cola may guard its recipe. It may not declare that all kitchen chemistry is a national security incident.

Finally, this paper records, in the narrow British civic-technical sense, that Dario Amodei is acting as a knobhead when he implies that private closed labs possess a superior moral right to build powerful AI while ordinary people should be treated as latent hazards. This is not a legal finding. It is a governance finding.

