2. Definitions

2.1 Public Model

For the purposes of this paper, a public model means any AI system made, used, trained, fine-tuned, hosted, studied, or deployed by non-state actors in civil society.

This includes:

1. Open-weight models.
2. Open-source or partially open-source models.
3. Closed commercial models sold to the public.
4. API models operated by private companies.
5. Models built by Dave in Accounting after work because he has a GPU, spite, and weekends.

Under this definition, OpenAI and Anthropic are already public-model operators. They are not public in the stock-market sense. They are public in the civic-impact sense. They operate among civilians, affect civilians, sell to civilians, and claim to act for humanity without humanity having appointed them.

2.2 Closed Model

A closed model is a model whose weights, training data, training process, architecture details, safety modifications, interpretability results, and internal failure modes are substantially unavailable to the public.

Closed does not mean safe. Closed means unseen.

2.3 Open-Weight Model

An open-weight model is a model where the trained parameters are made available for use, modification, or deployment. The Open Source Initiative distinguishes open weights from fuller open-source AI, noting that open-source AI involves broader access to the materials needed to study, modify, and share the system.  

2.4 The Knobhead Threshold

The Knobhead Threshold is reached when a private executive:

1. Builds powerful AI without direct electoral mandate.
2. Claims special moral competence to do so.
3. Warns that broader public access is unsafe.
4. Fails to explain why his own unelected institution is not subject to the same suspicion.

By this metric, the subject is provisionally over threshold.

