4. The Coca-Cola Equivalence Test

The Coca-Cola Equivalence Test asks:

Would we accept this argument from a soft-drink company?

Suppose Coca-Cola announced:

“Kitchen beverages are dangerous. Citizens may poison one another. Therefore, only Coca-Cola and a few trusted beverage labs should be allowed to mix liquids at scale.”

The public would correctly reply:

“You are a company. Sit down.”

The same principle applies to AI.

OpenAI and Anthropic may argue that they have better infrastructure, more staff, stronger testing, and greater visibility into frontier risks. Those claims may be relevant to regulation. They do not establish a natural right to monopoly.

A company can argue for licensing.
A company can argue for standards.
A company can argue for audits.
A company can argue for liability.
A company cannot argue that its own private fear of competitors is identical to public safety.

