5. Methodology: The Recursive Legitimacy Audit

The Office applied the Recursive Legitimacy Audit, also known as RLA-7, to determine whether closed frontier labs possess a superior right to build AI.

5.1 Test One: Democratic Mandate

Question: Were the relevant executives elected by the public to decide who may build advanced AI?

Finding: No.

5.2 Test Two: Symmetry of Danger

Question: If open models are dangerous because powerful AI can be misused, are closed corporate models also dangerous?

Finding: Yes.

5.3 Test Three: Visibility

Question: Does secrecy itself prove safety?

Finding: No. Secrecy proves only that fewer outsiders can inspect the danger.

5.4 Test Four: Institutional Self-Exemption

Question: Does a private lab’s claim to care about humanity exempt it from the risks it attributes to others?

Finding: Absolutely not.

5.5 Test Five: The Dave-in-Accounting Standard

Question: Is Dario Amodei inherently more democratically legitimate than Dave in Accounting?

Finding: No. Dario may have more compute, credentials, and investor confidence. Dave may have a spreadsheet. Neither has been crowned Minister of Thought.

