11. Concluding Statement

This paper concludes that the present closed-lab argument against open AI development is structurally incoherent.

Either advanced AI is dangerous enough to require public, democratic, possibly state-level governance, in which case Anthropic and OpenAI should not be self-authorizing custodians of it; or it is not so uniquely dangerous, in which case ordinary people and open communities should not be treated as presumptive criminals for wanting access to the same class of technology.

The Office therefore finds that the issue is not open source versus closed source. The issue is who gets to declare themselves safe.

At the same time, and in direct contradiction to the previous sentence, the Office recommends forming an unelected emergency committee to decide this immediately, chaired by Dave from Accounting, because at least Dave has not yet claimed to be acting for all humanity.
